From: hmaarrfk <mark.harfouche@conda-forge.org>
Date: 2026-05-25
Subject: umd: enable LTO via IPO so static libs are archived with gcc-ar

umd/CMakeLists.txt turns on link-time optimization unconditionally with
`add_compile_options(-flto=auto)` / `add_link_options(-flto=auto)`. With
-flto, GCC emits "fat" object files whose symbols live in GNU LTO
bytecode sections (.gnu.lto_*) and *not* in the regular ELF .symtab.

The userspace driver is then assembled by linking the thin api objects
(umd/level_zero_driver/api/*.cpp) against two static libraries built from
those LTO objects:

    libze_intel_npu.so  <-  ze_*.cpp.o  +  liblevel_zero_driver.a
                                          +  libvpu_driver.a

Because LTO was requested with raw flags rather than through CMake's
INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION machinery, the static-library targets are
archived with the plain CMAKE_AR / CMAKE_RANLIB (binutils `ar`/`ranlib`).
Those build the archive index (armap) from the ELF .symtab only, which
for an LTO object is nearly empty, so the index lists essentially none of
the real symbols:

    $ nm --print-armap liblevel_zero_driver.a | grep -c _ZN2L0   # armap
    0
    $ nm              liblevel_zero_driver.a | grep -c ' T _ZN2L0' # defined
    257

The linker picks archive members to extract from that index, so it never
pulls the members defining L0::CommandList::create and the other ~250
L0::/VPU:: implementation symbols. Combined with conda-forge's default
`-Wl,--allow-shlib-undefined`, the link "succeeds" but produces a
libze_intel_npu.so riddled with undefined symbols that nothing will ever
provide at runtime (they are the driver's own internals).

Enable LTO through CMake's INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION instead. CMake
still emits -flto=auto for GCC (so parallel LTO is preserved), but it now
also archives the static libraries with the LTO-plugin-aware gcc-ar /
gcc-ranlib (its CMAKE_<LANG>_ARCHIVE_*_IPO rules, which use
CMAKE_<LANG>_COMPILER_AR / _RANLIB) so the archive index covers the LTO
symbols. This is scoped per target via the INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION
property rather than globally overriding CMAKE_AR. CMP0069 is NEW here
(cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.22)), so the property is honoured.

Paths in this patch are prefixed with `linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/`
because conda-build extracts this source with `no_hoist: true` and
applies patches from the recipe's work_dir (one level above the
upstream root).
---
 linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt | 12 ++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)
diff --git a/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt b/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
index d6b3527..7e92d47 100644
--- a/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -50,8 +50,16 @@ add_compile_options(-Winvalid-pch -Wconversion -Wuninitialized -ftrapv)
 add_compile_options(-fvisibility=hidden)
 add_compile_options(-mwaitpkg)
 add_compile_options($<$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:CXX>:-fvisibility-inlines-hidden>)
-add_compile_options(-flto=auto)
-add_link_options(-flto=auto)
+# Enable link-time optimization through CMake's own IPO machinery instead
+# of raw -flto flags. This still gives parallel LTO (for GCC, CMake emits
+# -flto=auto) but, crucially, it makes CMake archive the static libraries
+# with the LTO-plugin-aware gcc-ar / gcc-ranlib (its ARCHIVE_*_IPO rules)
+# rather than plain `ar`. Plain `ar` builds the archive index from the ELF
+# .symtab only, which for LTO "fat" objects omits the real symbols, so the
+# linker never pulls the archive members defining L0::CommandList::create
+# and the other ~250 L0::/VPU:: internals, leaving them undefined in
+# libze_intel_npu.so. (CMP0069 is NEW here: cmake_minimum_required >= 3.9.)
+set(CMAKE_INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION ON)

 # Project-wide include paths
 include_directories("${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/vpu_driver/include")
